We remark here in passing that the force with which a string that has been violently stretched con· tracts to its original length arises from the same cause. For although the string itself may be a loose body, yet its minute fibres are somewhat rigid and their shape alters with the extension os the string. But the move· ment of the contracting string is caused by the effort of its fibres to revert to their original form.
